28    /**
29    * <p>Operations on {@link java.lang.String} that are
30    * {@code null} safe.</p>
31    *
32    * <ul>
33    * <li><b>IsEmpty/IsBlank</b>
34    * - checks if a String contains text</li>
35    * <li><b>Trim/Strip</b>
36    * - removes leading and trailing whitespace</li>
37    * <li><b>Equals</b>
38    * - compares two strings null-safe</li>
39    * <li><b>startsWith</b>
40    * - check if a String starts with a prefix null-safe</li>
41    * <li><b>endsWith</b>
42    * - check if a String ends with a suffix null-safe</li>
43    * <li><b>IndexOf/LastIndexOf/Contains</b>
44    * - null-safe index-of checks
45    * <li><b>IndexOfAny/LastIndexOfAny/IndexOfAnyBut/LastIndexOfAnyBut</b>
46    * - index-of any of a set of Strings</li>
47    * <li><b>ContainsOnly/ContainsNone/ContainsAny</b>
48    * - does String contains only/none/any of these characters</li>
49    * <li><b>Substring/Left/Right/Mid</b>
50    * - null-safe substring extractions</li>
51    * <li><b>SubstringBefore/SubstringAfter/SubstringBetween</b>
52    * - substring extraction relative to other strings</li>
53    * <li><b>Split/Join</b>
54    * - splits a String into an array of substrings and vice versa</li>
55    * <li><b>Remove/Delete</b>
56    * - removes part of a String</li>
57    * <li><b>Replace/Overlay</b>
58    * - Searches a String and replaces one String with another</li>
59    * <li><b>Chomp/Chop</b>
60    * - removes the last part of a String</li>
61    * <li><b>AppendIfMissing</b>
62    * - appends a suffix to the end of the String if not present</li>
63    * <li><b>PrependIfMissing</b>
64    * - prepends a prefix to the start of the String if not present</li>
65    * <li><b>LeftPad/RightPad/Center/Repeat</b>
66    * - pads a String</li>
67    * <li><b>UpperCase/LowerCase/SwapCase/Capitalize/Uncapitalize</b>
68    * - changes the case of a String</li>
69    * <li><b>CountMatches</b>
70    * - counts the number of occurrences of one String in another</li>
71    * <li><b>IsAlpha/IsNumeric/IsWhitespace/IsAsciiPrintable</b>
72    * - checks the characters in a String</li>
73    * <li><b>DefaultString</b>
74    * - protects against a null input String</li>
75    * <li><b>Reverse/ReverseDelimited</b>
76    * - reverses a String</li>
77    * <li><b>Abbreviate</b>
78    * - abbreviates a string using ellipsis</li>
79    * <li><b>Difference</b>
80    * - compares Strings and reports on their differences</li>
81    * <li><b>LevenshteinDistance</b>
82    * - the number of changes needed to change one String into another</li>
83    * </ul>
84    *
85    * <p>The {@code StringUtils} class defines certain words related to
86    * String handling.</p>
87    *
88    * <ul>
89    * <li>null - {@code null}</li>
90    * <li>empty - a zero-length string ({@code ""})</li>
91    * <li>space - the space character ({@code ' '}, char 32)</li>
92    * <li>whitespace - the characters defined by {@link Character#isWhitespace(char)}</li>
93    * <li>trim - the characters &lt;= 32 as in {@link String#trim()}</li>
94    * </ul>
95    *
96    * <p>{@code StringUtils} handles {@code null} input Strings quietly.
97    * That is to say that a {@code null} input will return {@code null}.
98    * Where a {@code boolean} or {@code int} is being returned
99    * details vary by method.</p>
100    *
101    * <p>A side effect of the {@code null} handling is that a
102    * {@code NullPointerException} should be considered a bug in
103    * {@code StringUtils}.</p>
104    *
105    * <p>Methods in this class give sample code to explain their operation.
106    * The symbol {@code *} is used to indicate any input including {@code null}.</p>
107    *
108    * <p>#ThreadSafe#</p>
109    * @see java.lang.String
110    * @since 1.0
111    * @version $Id$
112    */
113    //@Immutable
 
97.6% Uncovered Elements: 61 (2,504) Complexity: 790 Complexity Density: 0.58
114    public class StringUtils {
115    // Performance testing notes (JDK 1.4, Jul03, scolebourne)
116    // Whitespace:
117    // Character.isWhitespace() is faster than WHITESPACE.indexOf()
118    // where WHITESPACE is a string of all whitespace characters
119    //
120    // Character access:
121    // String.charAt(n) versus toCharArray(), then array[n]
122    // String.charAt(n) is about 15% worse for a 10K string
123    // They are about equal for a length 50 string
124    // String.charAt(n) is about 4 times better for a length 3 string
125    // String.charAt(n) is best bet overall
126    //
127    // Append:
128    // String.concat about twice as fast as StringBuffer.append
129    // (not sure who tested this)
130

173    /**
174    * A regex pattern for recognizing blocks of whitespace characters.
175    * The apparent convolutedness of the pattern serves the purpose of
176    * ignoring "blocks" consisting of only a single space: the pattern
177    * is used only to normalize whitespace, condensing "blocks" down to a
178    * single space, thus matching the same would likely cause a great
179    * many noop replacements.
180    */
181    private static final Pattern WHITESPACE_PATTERN = Pattern.compile("(?: \\s|[\\s&&[^ ]])\\s*");
182

6251    /**
6252    * <p>Abbreviates a String using ellipses. This will turn
6253    * "Now is the time for all good men" into "...is the time for..."</p>
6254    *
6255    * <p>Works like {@code abbreviate(String, int)}, but allows you to specify
6256    * a "left edge" offset. Note that this left edge is not necessarily going to
6257    * be the leftmost character in the result, or the first character following the
6258    * ellipses, but it will appear somewhere in the result.

6634  24 public static int getLevenshteinDistance(CharSequence s, CharSequence t) {...
6635  24 if (s == null || t == null) {
6636  4 throw new IllegalArgumentException("Strings must not be null");
6637    }
6638   
6639    /*
6640    The difference between this impl. and the previous is that, rather
6641    than creating and retaining a matrix of size s.length() + 1 by t.length() + 1,
6642    we maintain two single-dimensional arrays of length s.length() + 1. The first, d,
6643    is the 'current working' distance array that maintains the newest distance cost
6644    counts as we iterate through the characters of String s. Each time we increment
6645    the index of String t we are comparing, d is copied to p, the second int[]. Doing so
6646    allows us to retain the previous cost counts as required by the algorithm (taking
6647    the minimum of the cost count to the left, up one, and diagonally up and to the left
6648    of the current cost count being calculated). (Note that the arrays aren't really
6649    copied anymore, just switched...this is clearly much better than cloning an array
6650    or doing a System.arraycopy() each time through the outer loop.)
6651   
6652    Effectively, the difference between the two implementations is this one does not
6653    cause an out of memory condition when calculating the LD over two very large strings.
6654    */
6655   
6656  20 int n = s.length(); // length of s
6657  20 int m = t.length(); // length of t
6658   
6659  20 if (n == 0) {
6660  4 return m;
6661  16 } else if (m == 0) {
6662  2 return n;
6663    }
6664   
6665  14 if (n > m) {
6666    // swap the input strings to consume less memory
6667  6 final CharSequence tmp = s;
6668  6 s = t;
6669  6 t = tmp;
6670  6 n = m;
6671  6 m = t.length();
6672    }
6673   
6674  14 int p[] = new int[n + 1]; //'previous' cost array, horizontally
6675  14 int d[] = new int[n + 1]; // cost array, horizontally
6676  14 int _d[]; //placeholder to assist in swapping p and d
6677   
6678    // indexes into strings s and t
6679  14 int i; // iterates through s
6680  14 int j; // iterates through t
6681   
6682  14 char t_j; // jth character of t
6683   
6684  14 int cost; // cost
6685   
6686  90 for (i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
6687  76 p[i] = i;
6688    }
6689   
6690  102 for (j = 1; j <= m; j++) {
6691  88 t_j = t.charAt(j - 1);
6692  88 d[0] = j;
6693   
6694  500 for (i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
6695  412 cost = s.charAt(i - 1) == t_j ? 0 : 1;
6696    // minimum of cell to the left+1, to the top+1, diagonally left and up +cost
6697  412 d[i] = Math.min(Math.min(d[i - 1] + 1, p[i] + 1), p[i - 1] + cost);
6698    }
6699   
6700    // copy current distance counts to 'previous row' distance counts
6701  88 _d = p;
6702  88 p = d;
6703  88 d = _d;
6704    }

6707    // actually has the most recent cost counts

6709    }

6751    /*
6752    This implementation only computes the distance if it's less than or equal to the
6753    threshold value, returning -1 if it's greater. The advantage is performance: unbounded
6754    distance is O(nm), but a bound of k allows us to reduce it to O(km) time by only
6755    computing a diagonal stripe of width 2k + 1 of the cost table.
6756    It is also possible to use this to compute the unbounded Levenshtein distance by starting
6757    the threshold at 1 and doubling each time until the distance is found; this is O(dm), where
6758    d is the distance.
6759   
6760    One subtlety comes from needing to ignore entries on the border of our stripe
6761    eg.
6762    p[] = |#|#|#|*
6763    d[] = *|#|#|#|
6764    We must ignore the entry to the left of the leftmost member
6765    We must ignore the entry above the rightmost member
6766   
6767    Another subtlety comes from our stripe running off the matrix if the strings aren't
6768    of the same size. Since string s is always swapped to be the shorter of the two,
6769    the stripe will always run off to the upper right instead of the lower left of the matrix.
6770   
6771    As a concrete example, suppose s is of length 5, t is of length 7, and our threshold is 1.
6772    In this case we're going to walk a stripe of length 3. The matrix would look like so:
6773   
6774    1 2 3 4 5
6775    1 |#|#| | | |
6776    2 |#|#|#| | |
6777    3 | |#|#|#| |
6778    4 | | |#|#|#|
6779    5 | | | |#|#|
6780    6 | | | | |#|
6781    7 | | | | | |
6782   
6783    Note how the stripe leads off the table as there is no possible way to turn a string of length 5
6784    into one of length 7 in edit distance of 1.
6785   
6786    Additionally, this implementation decreases memory usage by using two
6787    single-dimensional arrays and swapping them back and forth instead of allocating
6788    an entire n by m matrix. This requires a few minor changes, such as immediately returning
6789    when it's detected that the stripe has run off the matrix and initially filling the arrays with
6790    large values so that entries we don't compute are ignored.
6791   
6792    See Algorithms on Strings, Trees and Sequences by Dan Gusfield for some discussion.
6793    */
6794   
6795  62 int n = s.length(); // length of s
6796  62 int m = t.length(); // length of t
6797   
6798    // if one string is empty, the edit distance is necessarily the length of the other
6799  62 if (n == 0) {
6800  2 return m <= threshold ? m : -1;
6801  60 } else if (m == 0) {
6802  6 return n <= threshold ? n : -1;
6803    }
6804   
6805  54 if (n > m) {
6806    // swap the two strings to consume less memory
6807  22 final CharSequence tmp = s;
6808  22 s = t;
6809  22 t = tmp;
6810  22 n = m;
6811  22 m = t.length();
6812    }
6813   
6814  54 int p[] = new int[n + 1]; // 'previous' cost array, horizontally
6815  54 int d[] = new int[n + 1]; // cost array, horizontally
6816  54 int _d[]; // placeholder to assist in swapping p and d
6817   
6818    // fill in starting table values
6819  54 final int boundary = Math.min(n, threshold) + 1;
6820  216 for (int i = 0; i < boundary; i++) {
6821  162 p[i] = i;
6822    }
6823    // these fills ensure that the value above the rightmost entry of our
6824    // stripe will be ignored in following loop iterations
6825  54 Arrays.fill(p, boundary, p.length, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
6826  54 Arrays.fill(d, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
6827   
6828    // iterates through t
6829  308 for (int j = 1; j <= m; j++) {
6830  262 final char t_j = t.charAt(j - 1); // jth character of t
6831  262 d[0] = j;
6832   
6833    // compute stripe indices, constrain to array size
6834  262 final int min = Math.max(1, j - threshold);
6835  262 final int max = Math.min(n, j + threshold);
6836   
6837    // the stripe may lead off of the table if s and t are of different sizes
6838  262 if (min > max) {
6839  8 return -1;
6840    }
6841   
6842    // ignore entry left of leftmost
6843  254 if (min > 1) {
6844  32 d[min - 1] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
6845    }
6846   
6847    // iterates through [min, max] in s
6848  984 for (int i = min; i <= max; i++) {
6849  730 if (s.charAt(i - 1) == t_j) {
6850    // diagonally left and up
6851  74 d[i] = p[i - 1];
6852    } else {
6853    // 1 + minimum of cell to the left, to the top, diagonally left and up
6854  656 d[i] = 1 + Math.min(Math.min(d[i - 1], p[i]), p[i - 1]);
6855    }
6856    }
6857   
6858    // copy current distance counts to 'previous row' distance counts
6859  254 _d = p;
6860  254 p = d;
6861  254 d = _d;
6862    }
6863   
6864    // if p[n] is greater than the threshold, there's no guarantee on it being the correct
6865    // distance
6866  46 if (p[n] <= threshold) {
6867  30 return p[n];
6868    }
6869  16 return -1;
6870    }

7058    /**
7059    * <p>
7060    * Similar to <a
7061    * href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize-space">http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize
7062    * -space</a>
7063    * </p>
7064    * <p>
7065    * The function returns the argument string with whitespace normalized by using
7066    * <code>{@link #trim(String)}</code> to remove leading and trailing whitespace
7067    * and then replacing sequences of whitespace characters by a single space.
7068    * </p>
7069    * In XML Whitespace characters are the same as those allowed by the <a
7070    * href="http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-xml/#NT-S">S</a> production, which is S ::= (#x20 | #x9 | #xD | #xA)+
7071    * <p>
7072    * Java's regexp pattern \s defines whitespace as [ \t\n\x0B\f\r]
7073    * <p>
7074    * For reference:
7075    * <ul>
7076    * <li>\x0B = vertical tab</li>
7077    * <li>\f = #xC = form feed</li>
7078    * <li>#x20 = space</li>
7079    * <li>#x9 = \t</li>
7080    * <li>#xA = \n</li>
7081    * <li>#xD = \r</li>
7082    * </ul>
7083    * </p>
7084    * <p>
7085    * The difference is that Java's whitespace includes vertical tab and form feed, which this functional will also
7086    * normalize. Additionally <code>{@link #trim(String)}</code> removes control characters (char &lt;= 32) from both
7087    * ends of this String.
7088    * </p>
7089    *
7090    * @see Pattern
7091    * @see #trim(String)
7092    * @see <a
7093    * href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize-space">http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize-space</a>
7094    * @param str the source String to normalize whitespaces from, may be null
7095    * @return the modified string with whitespace normalized, {@code null} if null String input
7096    *
7097    * @since 3.0
7098    */
